Imperfect Derivations

Costs/Hours Used in 2023

It was assumed that full costs and hours were used for any survey where the data acquisition step was completed, regardless of whether later steps in the survey cycle were completed.

Expected Surveys for 2024

The list of expected surveys for 2024 was based on predictions of the next scheduled year for each survey, derived under the assumption of no changes in survey frequency over time.

If there was at least one year of reporting where data acquisition was scheduled (defined by Acquired = TRUE or Acquired = FALSE with any reason selected other than âNot Scheduledâ), the maximum among them was used as the most recent known year of the survey being scheduled, hereinafter denoted âxâ. If there were no years of reported scheduled data acquisition, the survey start year was used as the value of âxâ. The survey frequency was then iteratively applied to âxâ until a year of 2024 or later was reached.

If the prediction for the next scheduled survey year exceeded the end year of the survey, the next scheduled year was replaced with the end year value.

Count of Work Days and Percent of Work Year

These values assume an 8-hour work day and a 251-day (weekdays minus federal holidays) work year (varies slightly by year).

Non-Labor Operations Cost Total

If this field was left blank in PRIMR, an operations cost of $0 was assumed.

Pertaining to pROCs (Boolean)

A species list (scientific names) for each survey was compiled starting with listed and non-listed species, if provided. If âspeciesâ provided were only one word, this was assumed to be a genus, and all species of that genus in the refugeâs NWRspecies records were added to the species list for the survey. If no species were provided, the level 2 biotic groups were instead used. The biotic group scientific name was matched to a taxanomic order in the refugeâs NWRSpecies data, and all species of that order were added to the species list for the survey. If the biotic group did not match any orders in the NWRSpecies data, it instead was matched to a family, and the same procedures were applied.

The pROC list for the refuge was compiled from nROC scientific names in our IMP dataset and was supplemented with known synonyms of taxa when applicable. If any species in a surveyâs species list was found in the pROC list, this field was set to âTRUEâ.

Limitations

  1. Inability to accurately predict upcoming scheduled surveys

There are limited frequency options: sporadic/ad hoc, once, yearly, 2 years, 3 years, 4 years, 5 years, and 10 years.

Surveys with âsporadicâ or âonceâ frequencies are not possible to predict scheduling for.

The frequency and startDate fields fail to capture changes in frequency over time and unplanned gaps, which we know occur with many long-term surveys.

Note: not all âscheduledâ surveys are expected to occur.

  1. Inability to accurately determine time and money spent on partially completed surveys

According to the PRIMR help documentation, the staff time fields should be filled out as follows:

âYou need to account for all aspects of the survey including time spent on protocol development

(design), data entry, management, analysis and report writing (i.e., not just the costs of collecting

data).â

Staff time, which is also used in the calculation for total operations cost, is not broken up by survey step, so time spent cannot be accurately determined for partially completed surveys. My current method, which assumes total time and costs were spent if data was acquired, is inaccurate if refuge staff fill in this field as directed.

We do not know if refuges are correctly interpreting this field, are answering consistently, or are making accurate estimations.

  1. Inability to reliably determine individual workload from available time information

PRIMR only captures the total survey hours by survey coordinator. This does not account for time allocated between supporting staff on those surveys. Coordinators with more support staff may be able to accommodate annual survey hours greater than their total available hours because the survey hours are being completed by other staff, while coordinators without support staff cannot. As such, total hours also does not necessarily equate to total workload for a coordinator.

Note that total costs are supposed to take into account relative workloads of support staff. See PRIMR Help documentation below regarding the average salary (Average FWS FTE Cost Yearly) field:

âWhen survey tasks include personnel with different pay rates, the average should be weighted by the time anticipated for each person.â


  1. Difficulty efficiently and programmatically determining if a survey pertains to a pROC

Challenge 1: Because taxonomy is dynamic and species names are sometimes split up into multiple species with more time and information, we end up with outdated species names that cannot be matched without knowing the synonymous scientific names. Caylen and I have uncovered 17 taxa in pROC/PRIMR data with scientific name synonyms, but there may be more. These may need to be compiled from NWRSpecies data to obtain a comprehensive set.

Challenge 2: Some of our pROC data contains typos. Caylen and I have found 3 scientific name typos.

Challenge 3: Not all surveys have species-level taxonomy information (listedSpecies or nonListedSpecies fields) supplied in PRIMR, especially those dealing with broader categories of taxa, such as landbirds or waterfowl (see Example Data #5). Instead, we only have biotic group information (see screenshot example below).

Challenge 4: Not all surveys with populated listedSpecies or nonListedSpecies fields have information at the species level. Some instead list âspeciesâ at the genus level.

Challenge 5: Surveys pertaining to abiotic resources (e.g.Â water quality, carbon, snow) are left out when using species information for prioritization (see Example Data #5).

Questions To Consider

  1. Is survey planning a need such that we want to capture more standardized timing information (e.g., be able to create annual Gantt charts by refuge)? If so, is this something PRIMR should do? Is it something we want badly enough that we would consider collecting that information separately? Is this even in the realm of our responsibilities?

  2. We currently have no way of knowing which surveys are scheduled for a given year until a full year after the fact, assuming that reporting is completed and accurate. Is this an issue? Is there a solution?

  3. Are the estimates for costs and time in PRIMR accurate and detailed enough to make the conclusions we want to make? Do we need time breakdowns by survey lifecycle step?

  4. In an ideal world, should actual costs and time spent be captured in annual activity reporting?

  5. Do we want to create tools (or supply metrics) for prioritization? Are we able to given current resources? If so, what would these look like? Some ideas that I have already supplied for this test case include the time/financial costs, whether the survey is cooperative, whether the survey monitors a pROC, list of refuges that are also monitoring these species, and the IMP Table 1 survey ranking. Other ideas that have come up include additional species/survey scores determined during the pROC process and available species trend information.

  6. Is there information missing from PRIMR that is pertinent for survey continuation in the event of turnover?
